presented_choices:
["Step 1: Designate the leftmost object as Object A.

Step 2: Check if swapping Object A with its right neighbor is valid (based on a predefined rule, such as its weight).

If invalid, designate the right neighbor as the new Object A and repeat Step 2.

If valid, swap their positions, designate the swapped neighbor as Object B, note Object A’s position, and proceed to Step 3.

Step 3: Propagate Object B to the left, following the same logic as Step 2 but with two changes:

The goal direction is now left.

If a swap fails, assume Object B is sorted and return to Step 2 and remember Object A's position.","Start by comparing the first two blocks. Then progress by comparing the blocks in the 2nd and 3rd position, and then the 3rd and 4th, and so on.

Whenever a swap happens, keep note of the \"leading\" block that was placed ahead (to the right). If a swap does not happen, the block on the right that was compared becomes the new \"leading\" block. The block that was just swapped behind the \"leading\" block then needs to be compared to the block behind it. If a swap happens, again compare it to the block behind it. Repeat this until a swap does not happen or until it is placed in the first position. Then return to your \"leading\" block and compare it to the block ahead of it."]

If you swap in a rightly arranged sequence of 5 8 times, that's very out of order.","Instead of using a compare the first block to the second block, then compare the first block to the third block, etc., the Omgne Sort is a more direct and less repetitive sorting system which doesn't repeat steps over and over. The Omgne Sort compares the first block to the second and then the second to the third. Only when there is an actual block swap do you then go backwards in your possible swapping of blocks, i.e. if the fourth and fifth blocks swap, then you go backwards trying to swap blocks until they don't swap anymore."]
